# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-timestream
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-timestream/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:aws-timestream/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:aws-timestream/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:aws-timestream/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:aws-timestream/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
